            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;This language feature is hardly esoteric.  It&apos;s a fairly major feature of object construction.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;/users/168288/charles-salvia&quot; title=&quot;50,799 reputation&quot; class=&quot;comment-user&quot;&gt;Charles Salvia&lt;/a&gt;
                &lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-date&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;comment-link&quot; href=&quot;#comment1589217_1711990&quot;&gt;&lt;span title=&quot;2009-11-10 23:36:56Z, License: CC BY-SA 2.5&quot; class=&quot;relativetime-clean&quot;&gt;Nov 10, 2009 at 23:36&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;In fact, far from esoteric, you often have no choice but to use initializer lists. For example, if your class contains a &lt;code&gt;const&lt;/code&gt; member variable, or a reference, you have to use an initalizer list.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
